<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="386" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,151,823]" pageId="9" pageNumber="386">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,223,248]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="386" reason="1">Distribution.</emphasis>
Restricted to semidesertic habitats south of the plant free 
<collectingRegion box="[1002,1181,223,247]" country="Chile" name="Atacama" pageId="9" pageNumber="386">Atacama Desert</collectingRegion>
in north-central 
<collectingCountry box="[1368,1431,223,247]" name="Chile" pageId="9" pageNumber="386">Chile</collectingCountry>
, from the coastal dunes of the 
<typeStatus box="[491,539,260,284]" pageId="9" pageNumber="386">type</typeStatus>
locality at Playa Los Choros, 
<collectingRegion box="[886,1093,260,284]" country="Chile" name="Coquimbo" pageId="9" pageNumber="386">Coquimbo Region</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation box="[1110,1199,260,284]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1085,1108]" captionTargetBox="[226,1360,193,1064]" captionTargetId="figure-414@10.[226,1360,193,1064]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. (A) Eligmodontia dunaris MNHN 1547, paratype (Photo A. Spotorno). (B) Habitat at Playa Los Choros dunes, type locality (Photo C. Zuleta); intensive trapping at the plain belt (top, below sea border) failed to capture any Eligmodontia. (C) Eligmodontia dunaris captured and released alive at Caldera, Atacama, showing bipedal posture (Photo E. Valenzuela by permission)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5981094" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5981094/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="386">Fig. 7B</figureCitation>
), through the central plains 30 and 
<quantity box="[307,378,295,319]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" pageId="9" pageNumber="386" unit="km" value="55.0">55 km</quantity>
south of Copiapó city, 
<collectingRegion box="[640,830,295,319]" country="Chile" name="Atacama" pageId="9" pageNumber="386">Atacama Region</collectingRegion>
, and reaching the coasts of Copiapó, 
<collectingRegion box="[1248,1436,295,319]" country="Chile" name="Atacama" pageId="9" pageNumber="386">Atacama Region</collectingRegion>
at Playa Rodillo, 
<quantity box="[347,425,332,356]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="9" pageNumber="386" unit="km" value="1.5">1.5 km</quantity>
N of the Caldera port. Additionally, one living specimen identified by external characters was observed at a burrow entrance in sandy soil, captured and released alive at Bahia Salado, 
<quantity box="[1215,1287,367,391]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" pageId="9" pageNumber="386" unit="km" value="55.0">55 km</quantity>
S of Caldera (two photographs taken by Mr. Alvaro Sepulveda T.; not shown)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1340,439,464]" pageId="9" pageNumber="386" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,151,823]" box="[199,1340,439,464]" pageId="9" pageNumber="386">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,333,440,464]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="386" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name designates the preferred dunarian habitat of this new mammal species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="386" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,151,823]" pageId="9" pageNumber="386">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,475,500]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="386" reason="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
A member of the genus 
<emphasis box="[598,757,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="386">
<taxonomicName box="[598,753,476,500]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Eligmodontia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="9" pageNumber="386" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Eligmodontia</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
distinguishable from all the other species of the genus by its pygmy adult body size (total length ranging 
<quantity box="[647,793,511,535]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.39" metricValueMax="1.52" metricValueMin="1.26" pageId="9" pageNumber="386" unit="mm" value="139.0" valueMax="152.0" valueMin="126.0">126-152 mm</quantity>
, 
<tableCitation box="[805,889,511,535]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,241,1299,1323]" captionText="TABLE 2. Lengths (mm) and weights of adults in two species of Eligmodontia. Sample size (n), mean (X), standard deviation (SD), range with minimum and maximum values are given for each character. Significant differences (t-test; P&lt;0.05) were obtained for all characters." pageId="9" pageNumber="386">Table 2</tableCitation>
) and weight (range 
<quantity box="[1113,1229,511,535]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="1.2449999999999999" metricValueMax="1.55" metricValueMin="0.94" pageId="9" pageNumber="386" unit="g" value="12.45" valueMax="15.5" valueMin="9.4">9.4-15.5 g</quantity>
), as well as by the following combination of characters: small hind foot not larger than 
<quantity box="[923,1002,548,572]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="386" unit="mm" value="20.0">20 mm</quantity>
(range 
<quantity box="[1089,1208,548,572]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.85" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.7" pageId="9" pageNumber="386" unit="mm" value="18.5" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="17.0">17-20 mm</quantity>
, 
<tableCitation box="[1220,1305,548,572]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,241,1299,1323]" captionText="TABLE 2. Lengths (mm) and weights of adults in two species of Eligmodontia. Sample size (n), mean (X), standard deviation (SD), range with minimum and maximum values are given for each character. Significant differences (t-test; P&lt;0.05) were obtained for all characters." pageId="9" pageNumber="386">Table 2</tableCitation>
), very light dorsum yellowish brownish gray; whitish immaculate venter; tail without a pencil and whitish dorsally and ventrally slightly differentiated; length of tail slightly shorter than length of head and body; slightly darkish band present extending from nose to between the ears (
<figureCitation box="[703,793,655,679]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1085,1108]" captionTargetBox="[226,1360,193,1064]" captionTargetId="figure-414@10.[226,1360,193,1064]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. (A) Eligmodontia dunaris MNHN 1547, paratype (Photo A. Spotorno). (B) Habitat at Playa Los Choros dunes, type locality (Photo C. Zuleta); intensive trapping at the plain belt (top, below sea border) failed to capture any Eligmodontia. (C) Eligmodontia dunaris captured and released alive at Caldera, Atacama, showing bipedal posture (Photo E. Valenzuela by permission)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5981094" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5981094/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="386">Fig. 7A</figureCitation>
); ears with external short hairs rather homogenously light gray except a terminal fine dark line; greatest skull length generally 
<quantity box="[933,1096,692,716]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0799999999999996" metricValueMax="2.17" metricValueMin="1.9899999999999998" pageId="9" pageNumber="386" unit="mm" value="20.799999999999997" valueMax="21.7" valueMin="19.9">19.9-21.7 mm</quantity>
; length of maxillary toothrow generally 
<quantity box="[264,399,727,751]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="3.6" metricValueMin="3.4" pageId="9" pageNumber="386" unit="mm" value="3.5" valueMax="3.6" valueMin="3.4">3.4-3.6 mm</quantity>
; length of nasals 
<quantity box="[602,716,727,751]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.15" metricValueMax="8.3" metricValueMin="8.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="386" unit="mm" value="8.15" valueMax="8.3" valueMin="8.0">8-8.3 mm</quantity>
; anterior border of zygomatic plate slightly concave (
<figureCitation box="[1332,1422,727,751]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1936,1959]" captionTargetBox="[166,1406,865,1906]" captionTargetId="figure-390@9.[166,1410,865,1906]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 6. Eligmodontia dunaris MNHN 1546 (holotype): dorsal (A), ventral (B) and lateral (C) views of skull. Occlusal view of upper (F) and lower molars (I) of paratype LCM 3377. Similar views of E. puerulus LCM 1993 (D and G) and E. hirtipes LCM 1748 (E and H) are included for comparisons." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5981090" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5981090/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="386">Fig. 6C</figureCitation>
); rounded bullae and eustachian tubes poorly developed; moderately developed knobs at frontoparietal suture; braincase less inflated with auditory bullae barely visible in dorsal view (
<figureCitation box="[970,1060,799,823]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1936,1959]" captionTargetBox="[166,1406,865,1906]" captionTargetId="figure-390@9.[166,1410,865,1906]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 6. Eligmodontia dunaris MNHN 1546 (holotype): dorsal (A), ventral (B) and lateral (C) views of skull. Occlusal view of upper (F) and lower molars (I) of paratype LCM 3377. Similar views of E. puerulus LCM 1993 (D and G) and E. hirtipes LCM 1748 (E and H) are included for comparisons." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5981090" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5981090/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="386">Fig. 6A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
