<subSubSection lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="388" pageId="10" pageNumber="387" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,1244,2025]" pageId="10" pageNumber="387">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,523,1244,1269]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="387" reason="1">
Measurements of 
<typeStatus box="[414,519,1244,1268]" pageId="10" pageNumber="387">holotype</typeStatus>
.
</emphasis>
External measurements (in mm): total body length, 75; length of tail, 73; length of hind foot, 19; length of ear, 16. Weight: 
<quantity box="[640,713,1280,1305]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="1.53" pageId="10" pageNumber="387" unit="g" value="15.3">15.3 g</quantity>
. Cranial measurements (in mm): greatest length of skull, 21.81; width of braincase, 12.38; diastema, 4.6; nasal foramen, 4.2; palatal bridge, 3.9; bullar length less tube, 3.6; length of maxillary toothrow, 3.8; length of nasals, 8.9.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,1244,2025]" pageId="10" pageNumber="387">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,344,1388,1413]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="387" reason="1">Description.</emphasis>
The smallest body size among the species of the genus. Pelage is short, silky and lax. Coloration of the dorsum is light yellow brownish gray, usually darker in coastal or young specimens; venter is white; tail has no pencil and is usually whitish dorsally and ventrally with slight differentiation; tail length a little shorter than length of head and body. Ears of median size usually have whitish pre-auricular tufts reaching the proximal region, with terminally homogenous short light hairs. Color transition from dorsum to venter is sharp. Fore and hind feet are covered with white hairs (
<figureCitation box="[485,575,1568,1592]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1085,1108]" captionTargetBox="[226,1360,193,1064]" captionTargetId="figure-414@10.[226,1360,193,1064]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. (A) Eligmodontia dunaris MNHN 1547, paratype (Photo A. Spotorno). (B) Habitat at Playa Los Choros dunes, type locality (Photo C. Zuleta); intensive trapping at the plain belt (top, below sea border) failed to capture any Eligmodontia. (C) Eligmodontia dunaris captured and released alive at Caldera, Atacama, showing bipedal posture (Photo E. Valenzuela by permission)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5981094" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5981094/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="387">Fig. 7A</figureCitation>
). Hind feet are elongated; plantar pads D2-4 fused forming a large pad, with hypothenar pad absent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,1244,2025]" pageId="10" pageNumber="387">
Skull is delicate, with rostrum rather short and eyes rather large, giving a juvenile appearance (
<figureCitation box="[1252,1343,1640,1664]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1085,1108]" captionTargetBox="[226,1360,193,1064]" captionTargetId="figure-414@10.[226,1360,193,1064]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. (A) Eligmodontia dunaris MNHN 1547, paratype (Photo A. Spotorno). (B) Habitat at Playa Los Choros dunes, type locality (Photo C. Zuleta); intensive trapping at the plain belt (top, below sea border) failed to capture any Eligmodontia. (C) Eligmodontia dunaris captured and released alive at Caldera, Atacama, showing bipedal posture (Photo E. Valenzuela by permission)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5981094" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5981094/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="387">Fig. 7A</figureCitation>
). Nasals not extending beyond premaxillary-frontal suture (
<figureCitation box="[741,836,1676,1700]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1936,1959]" captionTargetBox="[166,1406,865,1906]" captionTargetId="figure-390@9.[166,1410,865,1906]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 6. Eligmodontia dunaris MNHN 1546 (holotype): dorsal (A), ventral (B) and lateral (C) views of skull. Occlusal view of upper (F) and lower molars (I) of paratype LCM 3377. Similar views of E. puerulus LCM 1993 (D and G) and E. hirtipes LCM 1748 (E and H) are included for comparisons." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5981090" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5981090/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="387">Fig. 6A</figureCitation>
). Incisive foramina short, the posterior margin just reaching M1 (
<figureCitation box="[308,396,1712,1736]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1936,1959]" captionTargetBox="[166,1406,865,1906]" captionTargetId="figure-390@9.[166,1410,865,1906]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 6. Eligmodontia dunaris MNHN 1546 (holotype): dorsal (A), ventral (B) and lateral (C) views of skull. Occlusal view of upper (F) and lower molars (I) of paratype LCM 3377. Similar views of E. puerulus LCM 1993 (D and G) and E. hirtipes LCM 1748 (E and H) are included for comparisons." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5981090" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5981090/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="387">Fig. 6B</figureCitation>
). Palate long, extending beyond the posterior plane of M3. Posterolateral palatal pits anterior to mesopterygoid fossa. Small bullae not very inflated, with eustachian tubes short, not reaching the posterior edge of parapterygoid processes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,1244,2025]" pageId="10" pageNumber="387">
Upper incisors opistodont, ungrooved, and pigmented orange in front. Maxillary toothrows slightly posteriorly convergent. Primary cusps of molars alternate. M1 with anteriomedian flexus absent (
<figureCitation box="[1110,1189,1856,1880]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1936,1959]" captionTargetBox="[166,1406,865,1906]" captionTargetId="figure-390@9.[166,1410,865,1906]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 6. Eligmodontia dunaris MNHN 1546 (holotype): dorsal (A), ventral (B) and lateral (C) views of skull. Occlusal view of upper (F) and lower molars (I) of paratype LCM 3377. Similar views of E. puerulus LCM 1993 (D and G) and E. hirtipes LCM 1748 (E and H) are included for comparisons." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5981090" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5981090/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="387">Fig. 6I</figureCitation>
). M2 with hypoflexus and metaflexus open and lophs and styles absent. M3 with hypoflexus present. m1 with well-developed procingulum; m2 with anterolophid absent; m3 with hypoflexid present.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,1244,2025]" lastBlockId="11.[151,1437,151,1292]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="388" pageId="10" pageNumber="387">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,365,1964,1989]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="387" reason="1">Comparisons.</emphasis>
This rare species has the smallest adult body size among all the species of the genus, as well as among all terrestrial mammals of 
<collectingCountry box="[532,596,2000,2024]" name="Chile" pageId="10" pageNumber="387">Chile</collectingCountry>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="LCM" authorityYear="1748" box="[607,852,2000,2024]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Eligmodontia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="10" pageNumber="387" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hirtipes">
<emphasis box="[607,852,2000,2024]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="387">Eligmodontia hirtipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be distinguished by the following: larger body size (
<tableCitation box="[213,305,151,175]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,241,1299,1323]" captionText="TABLE 2. Lengths (mm) and weights of adults in two species of Eligmodontia. Sample size (n), mean (X), standard deviation (SD), range with minimum and maximum values are given for each character. Significant differences (t-test; P&lt;0.05) were obtained for all characters." pageId="11" pageNumber="388">Table 2</tableCitation>
); hind foot always larger than 
<quantity box="[675,761,151,175]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" unit="mm" value="20.0">20 mm</quantity>
, dorsum usually darker, with an external almost blackish terminal wide band at the ears, particularly in juveniles; larger and oblong well-inflated bullae with posterior border almost reaching the anterior border of the foramen magnum; palatal width always larger than 
<quantity box="[1346,1435,223,247]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.6" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" unit="mm" value="2.6">2.6 mm</quantity>
(intermolar in 
<tableCitation box="[313,398,260,284]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,241,1299,1323]" captionText="TABLE 2. Lengths (mm) and weights of adults in two species of Eligmodontia. Sample size (n), mean (X), standard deviation (SD), range with minimum and maximum values are given for each character. Significant differences (t-test; P&lt;0.05) were obtained for all characters." pageId="11" pageNumber="388">Table 2</tableCitation>
); larger incisive foramen (&gt; 
<quantity box="[719,809,260,284]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.6" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" unit="mm" value="4.6">4.6 mm</quantity>
); posterior border of nasals extends beyond the plane of anterior border of optical foramen; antorbital foramen more rounded and anteriorly convergent; anterior border of zygomatic plate usually straight, not concave; and posterior upper border of optic foramen rather smooth. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="LCM" authorityYear="1993" box="[151,409,368,392]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Eligmodontia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="puerulus">
<emphasis box="[151,409,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="388">Eligmodontia puerulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished by the following external characters: larger body size (81.3± 
<quantity box="[1289,1380,367,391]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.1" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" unit="mm" value="4.1">4.1 mm</quantity>
), tail length (76.7±3.1), hindfoot (24.3± 
<quantity box="[535,622,404,428]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" unit="mm" value="0.8">0.8 mm</quantity>
) and ear length (17± 
<quantity box="[855,947,404,428]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" unit="mm" value="1.5">1.5 mm</quantity>
)(n=19).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,151,1292]" pageId="11" pageNumber="388">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,389,439,464]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" reason="1">Natural history.</emphasis>
Reproductively active individuals were captured in June, September and February-March. In 
<date box="[151,266,476,500]" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" value="2011-07">July 2011</date>
, a 
<quantity box="[303,356,476,500]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="1.4" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" unit="g" value="14.0">14 g</quantity>
female from Los Choros gave birth to four newborns after three weeks at the laboratory. In 
<date box="[151,299,511,535]" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" value="2011-08">August 2011</date>
, another 
<quantity box="[408,460,511,536]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="1.4" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" unit="g" value="14.0">14 g</quantity>
female from Los Choros gave birth to three 
<quantity box="[988,1047,511,536]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="2.1" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" unit="g" value="2.1">2.1 g</quantity>
newborns at the laboratory. Wild females weighing 13, 13 and 
<quantity box="[486,536,548,572]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="1.4" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" unit="g" value="14.0">14 g</quantity>
were pregnant with 5, 2, and 4 small embryos in September and March. Males weighing 13 and 
<quantity box="[346,396,583,608]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="1.6" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" unit="g" value="16.0">16 g</quantity>
had testes of 7x4 and 5x 
<quantity box="[677,746,583,607]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
. The stomach of one field specimen at Los Choros contained pieces of herbs, grains and insects; six young males and 
<specimenCount box="[802,942,620,644]" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" type="female">five females</specimenCount>
in the lab ate grains from commercial bird foods as well as cat food. This suggests a granivorous/omnivorous diet. Small mammal species reported or observed in the same habitat of the 
<typeStatus box="[545,643,692,716]" pageId="11" pageNumber="388">holotype</typeStatus>
included the ubiquitous sigmodontine rodent 
<taxonomicName box="[1154,1388,692,716]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Abrothrix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="olivaceous">
<emphasis box="[1154,1388,692,716]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="388">Abrothrix olivaceous</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the caviomorph 
<emphasis box="[292,512,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="388">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Molina" baseAuthorityYear="1782" box="[292,508,728,752]" class="Mammalia" family="Octodontidae" genus="Spalacopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cyanus">Spalacopus cyanus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and the gray fox 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1837" box="[709,911,728,752]" class="Mammalia" family="Canidae" genus="Lycalopex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="griseus">
<emphasis box="[709,911,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="388">Lycalopex griseus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,151,1292]" pageId="11" pageNumber="388">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,298,763,788]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" reason="1">Habitat.</emphasis>
The type locality is a sand dune belt of 
<quantity box="[768,841,764,788]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" unit="km" value="16.0">16 km</quantity>
in length and 
<quantity box="[1010,1089,764,788]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" unit="km" value="0.5">0.5 km</quantity>
in width (
<figureCitation box="[1211,1295,764,788]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1085,1108]" captionTargetBox="[226,1360,193,1064]" captionTargetId="figure-414@10.[226,1360,193,1064]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. (A) Eligmodontia dunaris MNHN 1547, paratype (Photo A. Spotorno). (B) Habitat at Playa Los Choros dunes, type locality (Photo C. Zuleta); intensive trapping at the plain belt (top, below sea border) failed to capture any Eligmodontia. (C) Eligmodontia dunaris captured and released alive at Caldera, Atacama, showing bipedal posture (Photo E. Valenzuela by permission)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5981094" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5981094/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="388">Fig. 7c</figureCitation>
). Four grids placed at the northern dunes with 50 standard Sherman-like traps set 
<quantity box="[1002,1066,799,823]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" unit="m" value="10.0">10 m</quantity>
apart, and active during three consecutive nights, captured only two 
<taxonomicName authorityName="MNHN" authorityYear="1547" box="[596,716,836,860]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Eligmodontia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dunaris">
<emphasis box="[596,716,836,860]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="388">E. dunaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
first, and 
<specimenCount box="[838,1010,836,860]" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" type="generic">four specimens</specimenCount>
six years later. Rains are scarce and irregular over time (
<bibRefCitation author="Armesto, J. &amp; Vidiella, P. &amp; Gutierrez, J." box="[378,609,871,896]" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" pagination="271 - 282" refId="ref9747" refString="Armesto, J., Vidiella, P. &amp; Gutierrez, J. (1993) Plant communities of the fog-free coastal desert of Chile: plant strategies in a fluctuating environment. Revista Chilena de Historia Natural, 66, 271 - 282." type="journal article" year="1993">
Armesto 
<emphasis box="[484,542,872,896]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="388">et al.</emphasis>
1993
</bibRefCitation>
); they occur in winter (from May to August), with an annual mean of 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" unit="mm" value="90.0">90 mm</quantity>
. There are dry years with less than 
<quantity box="[619,703,908,932]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" unit="mm" value="22.0">22 mm</quantity>
, and wet ones with more than 
<quantity box="[1066,1165,908,932]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" unit="mm" value="175.0">175 mm</quantity>
. Additional moisture is provided by local fog and rain. The plant cover is a xerophytic low matorral, with scarce small shrubs and herbs (
<figureCitation box="[159,249,980,1004]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1085,1108]" captionTargetBox="[226,1360,193,1064]" captionTargetId="figure-414@10.[226,1360,193,1064]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. (A) Eligmodontia dunaris MNHN 1547, paratype (Photo A. Spotorno). (B) Habitat at Playa Los Choros dunes, type locality (Photo C. Zuleta); intensive trapping at the plain belt (top, below sea border) failed to capture any Eligmodontia. (C) Eligmodontia dunaris captured and released alive at Caldera, Atacama, showing bipedal posture (Photo E. Valenzuela by permission)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5981094" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5981094/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="388">Fig. 7C</figureCitation>
), semi-dry most of the year. Plant cover was 43.9 % at the 
<typeStatus box="[931,1029,980,1004]" pageId="11" pageNumber="388">holotype</typeStatus>
site, mainly 
<taxonomicName box="[1178,1436,980,1004]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Cristaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="glaucophylla">
<emphasis box="[1178,1436,980,1004]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="388">Cristaria glaucophylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(13.4%), 
<taxonomicName box="[257,489,1016,1039]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Aizoaceae" genus="Tetragonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="maritima">
<emphasis box="[257,489,1016,1039]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="388">Tetragonia maritima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(8.1%), 
<taxonomicName box="[589,812,1016,1040]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Frankeniaceae" genus="Frankenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chilensis">
<emphasis box="[589,812,1016,1040]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="388">Frankenia chilensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(6.5%) and 
<taxonomicName box="[953,1159,1016,1040]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Nolana" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="divaricata">
<emphasis box="[953,1159,1016,1040]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="388">Nolana divaricata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(5.9%). Another similar grid set at the southern dunes (
<geoCoordinate box="[504,614,1052,1076]" degrees="29" direction="south" minutes="16" orientation="latitude" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" precision="925" value="-29.266666">29° 16´S</geoCoordinate>
– 
<geoCoordinate box="[630,749,1052,1076]" degrees="71" direction="west" minutes="18" orientation="longitude" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" precision="925" value="-71.3">71° 18´W</geoCoordinate>
, 
<quantity box="[762,853,1052,1076]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" unit="m" value="20.0">20 masl</quantity>
) captured a single individual only. The plant cover here was similar (35%), with 
<taxonomicName box="[491,618,1088,1112]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Frankeniaceae" genus="Frankenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="11" pageNumber="388" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chilensis">
<emphasis box="[491,618,1088,1112]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="388">F. chilensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(7.6%), 
